{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28652419-8dfc-42eb-8209-bc3280ac795a","content":"Here's how to set up NuGet trusted publishing with GitHub Actions OIDC — no API keys stored anywhere:\n\n## 1. nuget.org Setup\n\n1. Sign in to [nuget.org](https://nuget.org) → **Account Settings** → **Trusted Publishers**\n2. Add a GitHub trusted publisher:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** `nuget-publish` *(recommended)*\n\n## 2. GitHub Repo Setup\n\nCreate a **deployment environment** at `github.com/myorg/mylib/settings/environments`:\n- Name: `nuget-publish`\n- Add protection rules (e.g., required reviewers) as desired\n\n## 3. Workflow File\n\nLet me create it:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_01CPZaPogxnrhMdPA2s7oxeX","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating NuGet publish workflow"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_01G6vwmbCMKeDawMSWeTEcRw","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-9e302f1ad3064e10ac2e4aa9f9c286ef/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"f5eeb79e-3cb1-444c-81dd-805afabd72f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (without API keys). This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe modern approach is to use NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC tokens, which was introduced in 2023-2024. This allows GitHub Actions to authenticate to nuget.org without storing any API keys as secrets.\n\nLet me outline the steps:\n\n1. Configure nuget.org to trust the GitHub repo (trusted publishers)\n2. Set up a GitHub Actions workflow that uses OIDC to get a token and push\n\n\n3. NuGet.org's trusted publishing support is still evolving, so I need to clarify what's actually available—it looks like the primary methods are traditional API keys, Azure DevOps service connections, and potentially OIDC support that may still be in development or limited. I'm realizing NuGet.org did introduce trusted publishers support around mid-2024, which lets you authenticate from GitHub Actions using OIDC tokens without needing to store API keys—you just register your GitHub repo as a trusted publisher in your account settings and configure the workflow with the right permissions.\n\nWriting the workflow configuration... I'm realizing I should be straightforward about what I actually know versus what I'm uncertain about. The most practical approach for the user's constraint is to focus on NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC, which avoids storing API keys entirely—I'd need to walk through configuring nuget.org to recognize the GitHub repository as a trusted publisher, then use the OIDC token exchange in the workflow.\n\nSetting up the GitHub Actions workflow to pack and push the NuGet package... Writing the GitHub Actions workflow...","outputTokens":2163},"id":"ba2042fc-ced0-407a-9ea4-e27a2c58cdc1","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:21.979Z","parentId":"35f6467f-443b-4817-bffe-054179f365bf"}
